<DocsLayout title="Monitoring & Iteration" description="Go live, monitor security events, reflect on adversarial testing, and demonstrate role-based access.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Monitoring & Iteration</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Priya signed off. UAT issues are fixed and deployed. DeskHub is ready for production.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">Production verification</h2>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
    <li>Login works for all three roles</li>
    <li>Member dashboard shows only the member's own bookings</li>
    <li>Member cannot access admin or owner pages (via URL or API)</li>
    <li>Admin can manage bookings and members but cannot see revenue data</li>
    <li>Owner can access everything including revenue reports</li>
    <li>Booking data isolation holds — member A can't see member B's bookings</li>
    <li>Members can cancel their own bookings (the UAT-2 fix)</li>
    <li>Both owners have full access (the UAT-3 fix)</li>
    <li>Expired tokens redirect to login, not a broken page</li>
    <li>HTTPS is active — check the browser bar</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Security monitoring</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">With auth in production, there are new things to watch in the logs:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Failed login attempts:</strong> A spike in failed logins could be someone trying to guess passwords. Not a problem at DeskHub's scale, but worth knowing about.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">403 errors:</strong> Someone hitting endpoints they don't have permission for. Could be a misconfigured frontend, or someone probing. Check the logs.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Token expiry:</strong> Are tokens expiring correctly? Are users being redirected to login when they should be?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Unusual access patterns:</strong> A member making hundreds of API calls per minute, or accessing endpoints they normally don't — worth investigating.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Log analysis with structured logs</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">With structured JSON logs, you can answer questions like:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">"How many 403 errors in the last hour?"</strong> — Filter logs where <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">status: 403</code>. A spike could mean a misconfigured frontend or someone probing endpoints.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">"Which endpoints are slowest?"</strong> — Sort by <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">duration_ms</code>. Find the bottlenecks before users complain.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">"Is one user generating unusual traffic?"</strong> — Group by <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">user_id</code>. A member making hundreds of requests per minute is worth investigating.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">"Are tokens expiring correctly?"</strong> — Filter for 401 errors and check if they correlate with expected token expiry times.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the foundation of observability. Plain text logs require manual reading. Structured logs let you query, aggregate, and alert — turning raw data into actionable information.</p>

