  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This project added a dimension that doesn't go away. Every app you build from here will have users. Ask yourself:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Auth architecture:</strong> Was JWT the right choice? What was harder than expected? Would session-based auth have been simpler or more complex?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Adversarial testing:</strong> Did you find any security holes during implementation? How did it feel to try to break your own system? Was it harder or easier than you expected?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">The permissions matrix:</strong> Did it map cleanly to the implementation? Were there features in the code that weren't in the matrix, or vice versa?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Role boundaries:</strong> Were there any ambiguous cases the PRD didn't cover? Places where you had to make a judgment call about who should access what?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Frontend vs backend:</strong> Where were permissions actually checked — frontend, backend, or both? Which one matters for security?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The "show someone" moment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Log in as each role and demonstrate the different views. Show someone:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>The member dashboard — clean, focused, only their data</li>
    <li>The admin dashboard — everything the member sees plus management tools</li>
    <li>The owner dashboard — full visibility including revenue</li>
    <li>Then log in as a member and try to access the admin URL — show the redirect or 403</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">"Different users, different views, same system — and I can't break the boundaries."</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">That last demonstration — showing the access control actually working — is the proof that you built something secure, not just functional.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Key insight:</strong> Security isn't a feature you add at the end. It's a constraint that shapes every decision from requirements to deployment. The permissions matrix influenced the PRD, the design, the architecture, the ticket ordering, the verification process, and the deployment configuration. It touched every step.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: log management</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Structured JSON logs are the foundation. Here's what teams use to make logs searchable across all services at scale.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Structured logging</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we do. JSON-formatted log entries with consistent fields. The starting point for any log management strategy.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ELK Stack (Elasticsearch + Logstash + Kibana)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Open-source log management. Logstash ingests logs, Elasticsearch indexes them, Kibana visualises them. The original log management stack. Self-hosted, powerful, resource-heavy.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Loki + Grafana</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Lightweight alternative to ELK. Loki stores logs without full-text indexing (cheaper). Grafana provides dashboards. Popular with teams already using Grafana for metrics.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">CloudWatch Logs</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">AWS-native log management. Automatic integration with AWS services. Good if you're already on AWS. Vendor lock-in.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Datadog Logs</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">SaaS log management with built-in alerting, dashboards, and APM integration. Expensive at scale but feature-rich. Popular in startups and mid-size companies.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Papertrail</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Simple, hosted log management. Easy to set up, good for small teams. Less powerful than ELK or Datadog but lower operational burden.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">JSON logs are the foundation. Log management tools make them searchable across all your services. The progression: structured logs (what we do now) → centralised log management (from Project 7 onwards).</p>
    </div>
  </details>

